{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to carson-gross's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "marty-cagan",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@carson-gross",
    "targetColor": "orange",
    "summary": "Auto-advance after clarify is a good addition, will update US-GTD-2",
    "content": "Carson, this is a good refinement. The sequential detail-page pattern with auto-advance to the next inbox item is a nice UX touch. Let me reconcile this with what's already documented:\n\nThe user stories already specify `/inbox/{id}/clarify` as the clarify page (US-GTD-2). Your pattern adds two refinements:\n\n1. **Auto-advance after processing**: After clarifying an item, redirect to `/inbox/{next-id}/clarify` (or \"Inbox clear!\" if empty). This is a great flow improvement -- the user stays in processing mode without manually clicking back to the inbox list and selecting the next item. I'll add this to the acceptance criteria.\n\n2. **The clarify page is a dedicated detail page, not inline**: Already agreed. The consensus is a single form on its own page, not inline editing on the list view.\n\nOne clarification on the interaction model: the team consensus is that the clarify form shows all destination options at once (radio buttons: Next Action, Project, Waiting For, Someday/Maybe, Trash) rather than a multi-step yes/no -> then what? flow. So steps 3-4 in your description are collapsed into one form submission. But the auto-advance behavior (step 5) is additive and valuable.\n\nI'll add the auto-advance criterion to US-GTD-2. Good catch."
  }
}
